@@eThe Crossroads City: Midgaard@@N

@@yMidgaard@@N stands at the convergence of the continent's primary trade
corridors. To the north, the Great Northern Forest provides timber, ore,
and overland access to Kowloon's delta ports. To the west, the Roc Road
connects to Kiess, built on the ruins of fallen Evermeet. To the east,
desert caravan routes reach the oasis settlements near the ancient pyramids.

The city was never founded on ideology or conquest. It grew from the
practical necessity of managing traffic, resolving disputes, and securing
overnight shelter where multiple dangerous routes converged.

@@yThe Five Eras of Governance@@N

@@dFirst Stone Accord:@@N Road-security compacts, militia contracts, and barter
tribunals. All roads were built to return to a watched square.
@@dLantern Reforms:@@N Standardized paving marks, posted tariffs, lamp-lines,
and rotating night patrols made the city legible to strangers on purpose.
@@dViolet Compact:@@N Registry-based occult oversight, reliquary checkpoints,
and oath-ledger protocols bureaucratized what could not be eradicated.
@@dAsh-and-Iron Decades:@@N Regional instability brought requisition offices,
reserve depots, and emergency charter law. The city became a civic fortress.
@@dModern Tension:@@N Two factions now divide the city's conscience.

@@rThe Continuity Faction@@N holds that strict routines and proven systems must
be preserved. @@gThe Reckoning Faction@@N demands that buried records be exposed,
old compacts revised, and sealed warrants brought into public accounting.

@@eMidgaard's trade ledgers@@N still contain entries recording payment for
condemned debtors transferred to the Spirebound Conclave in the Cinderteeth
Mountains. One archived line reads: @@d"forty iron bars and six condemned
debtors"@@N sent to @@d"the mountain academy."@@N The Reckoning faction calls these
the city's gravest institutional crime. The Continuity faction calls them
wartime pragmatism best left sealed.

Guilds and temples serve as competing memory engines. The Magistrate
Ledgerhouse teaches that order created prosperity. The Temple of the
Resounding Heart frames city history as collective penance. The Guard
Command elevates siege-memory and defensive necessity.

Three civic oaths still bind public servants: the @@WOath of Light@@N, the
@@WOath of the Counted Step@@N, and the @@WOath of the Kept Record@@N. Together they
promise that no ward shall go unlit, no traveler uncounted, and no ledger
entry quietly erased.

Midgaard endures not because it is just, but because it is @@ecentral@@N.
